config.text: High Risk Attributes

The Safe Streets for All (SS4A) team conducted a Systemic Based (Risk/Causality) Analysis uses a machine learning model (Random Forest) that identifies features of the regional roadway and intersections that correlate with fatalities and serious injuries regardless of whether such events occurred recently. The goal is to flag infrastructure with roadway features (e.g., lane count) that may increase the likelihood of future severe incidents on the network. The resulting attribute of this work is a “Risk Score” that calls attention to particularly risky roadway and junction facilities and a High Risk Network.


The following are the top five highest correlated attributes that were used to determine high risk:


Intersections:

  • Average Lane Widths on approaches of 12 feet or more feet
  • Four or more number of legs
  • Posted Speed on an approach of 35 miles per hour or greater
  • 60/120 degree intersections
  • Four or more lanes on the major approach


Roads:

  • Designated as a Principal Arterial functional class
  • Posted Speed of 25 miles per hour or greater
  • No median or 16+ foot medians
  • Lane Width of 12 or more feet
  • Identified as an "Experienced Riders" bike facility route

Safety Need

The Safe Streets for All (SS4A) team utilize information on historical need to develop a High Priority Network (HPN). Find more information about each of those layers below:


  • Community Survey - Member of the community identified segments and junctions that were of safety concern. These points were utilized to develop the Community Survey Network. Click here to access the survey.
  • Crashes (2018-2022) - Five years of crash data from the Nebraska and Iowa Departments of Transportation were used to develop the High Injury Network and Risk Attributes used in the High Risk Network.
High Priority Network
Mean Priority Score

This score is the average (using mean) priority score of all the features shown on the map. The priority score is a combination of three scores (location, community, and risk) that has a maximum total value of 300. The mean priority score assists in finding the relation between different areas and safety priority.

config.text: The Community Survey Network is roads and intersections that were identified by the community to be of traffic safety concern.
The High Injury Network is roads and intersections with high fatal and serious injury crash rate based on 5 years of historic crash data.
The High Risk Network is roads and intersections with identified high risk attributes based on a machine learning analysis.

﻿Tool User Guide
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: The tool sets the groundwork for a targeted Safety Action Plan expected to be complete by Fall 2025. The analysis, utilizing 2018 – 2022 crash data through hotspot and systemic risk based analysis, underscores the critical areas where interventions can significantly enhance road safety and reduce fatal and serious injury crashes. Click the arrow to learn how to use the tool.
Layers Tab
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: Use the sidebar on the left to query to your location or specific network of interest. The location drop down allows users to select a City or County. The Underlying Networks display networks that are the basis of the High Priority Network. Within each network you can access the individual layers as the community survey, historic crash points, or descriptions of high risk fields.
﻿High Priority Network (HPN) Tool
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: The analysis sets the groundwork for a targeted Safety Action Plan expected to be complete by Fall 2025. The analysis, utilizing 2018 – 2022 crash data through hotspot and systemic risk based analysis, underscores the critical areas where interventions can significantly enhance road safety and reduce fatal and serious injury crashes.
Filters Tab
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: The second tab on the left can be used to parse the road and intersections layers down to highlighted corridors or individual attributes. Use the radio buttons to toggle on and off corridors and intersections with desired crash types. Use the drop down buttons to filter the roadway and intersections based on roadway attributes like number of lanes, speed limit, or intersection type.
Scoring Tab
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: Use this tab to either create your own priority network for export or adjust the threshold of the existing network. By clicking scoring button, the user can adjusting weight of the scoring variables used to create the High Priority Network. The composite layer created does not interact with the statistics sidebar. If the user desires interaction with the statistic sidebar, they can identify the minimum threshold of each of the scoring criteria to adjust the existing network and view the resultant statistics.
Network Statistics Tab
config.placeholder: Double click to edit text

config.text: The tab on the right contains information relative to your displayed view. Zooming or Filtering updates the stats relative to the viewed area. The statistics here are entirely relative to the filtered and displayed networks in blue. Use this tab to understand the amount of crashes, fatalities, serious injuries, or relative impact ratios compared to the complete network of that area.
